From: hmaarrfk <mark.harfouche@conda-forge.org>
Date: 2026-05-25
Subject: umd: use LTO-plugin-aware ar/ranlib so static-lib symbols resolve

umd/CMakeLists.txt turns on link-time optimization unconditionally with
`add_compile_options(-flto=auto)` / `add_link_options(-flto=auto)`. With
-flto, GCC emits "fat" object files whose symbols live in GNU LTO
bytecode sections (.gnu.lto_*) and *not* in the regular ELF .symtab.

The userspace driver is then assembled by linking the thin api objects
(umd/level_zero_driver/api/*.cpp) against two static libraries built from
those LTO objects:

    libze_intel_npu.so  <-  ze_*.cpp.o  +  liblevel_zero_driver.a
                                          +  libvpu_driver.a

CMake creates those archives with the plain binutils `ar`/`ranlib`
(CMAKE_AR), which only reads the ELF .symtab when building the archive
index (armap). For an LTO object the .symtab is almost empty, so the
armap ends up listing essentially none of the real symbols:

    $ nm --print-armap liblevel_zero_driver.a | grep -c _ZN2L0   # armap
    0
    $ nm              liblevel_zero_driver.a | grep -c ' T _ZN2L0' # defined
    257

The linker decides which archive members to extract from that index, so
it never pulls the members that define L0::CommandList::create and the
257 other L0:: implementation symbols. Combined with conda-forge's
default `-Wl,--allow-shlib-undefined`, the link "succeeds" but produces a
libze_intel_npu.so riddled with undefined symbols that nothing will ever
provide at runtime (they are the driver's own internals).

The fix is to build the archives with the compiler's LTO-plugin-aware
ar/ranlib wrappers (gcc-ar / gcc-ranlib). CMake already discovers these
as CMAKE_CXX_COMPILER_AR / CMAKE_CXX_COMPILER_RANLIB (it uses them itself
when LTO is enabled via CMAKE_INTERPROCEDURAL_OPTIMIZATION); point
CMAKE_AR / CMAKE_RANLIB at them so the armap covers the LTO symbols too.

Paths in this patch are prefixed with `linux-npu-driver-1.32.1/`
because conda-build extracts this source with `no_hoist: true` and
applies patches from the recipe's work_dir (one level above the
upstream root).
---
 linux-npu-driver-1.32.1/umd/CMakeLists.txt | 18 ++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 18 insertions(+)
diff --git a/linux-npu-driver-1.32.1/umd/CMakeLists.txt b/linux-npu-driver-1.32.1/umd/CMakeLists.txt
index d6b3527..6dbcb64 100644
--- a/linux-npu-driver-1.32.1/umd/CMakeLists.txt
+++ b/linux-npu-driver-1.32.1/umd/CMakeLists.txt
@@ -53,6 +53,24 @@ add_compile_options($<$<COMPILE_LANGUAGE:CXX>:-fvisibility-inlines-hidden>)
 add_compile_options(-flto=auto)
 add_link_options(-flto=auto)

+# Building with -flto emits "fat" object files whose symbols live in GNU
+# LTO bytecode sections (.gnu.lto_*) rather than in the regular ELF
+# .symtab. When such objects are collected into a static library
+# (level_zero_driver, vpu_driver), a plain `ar`/`ranlib` only reads the
+# ELF .symtab and therefore writes an archive index (armap) that omits
+# every LTO-only symbol. The linker uses that index to decide which
+# archive members to pull, so it never extracts the members defining e.g.
+# L0::CommandList::create and leaves them undefined in libze_intel_npu.so.
+# Use the compiler's LTO-plugin-aware ar/ranlib wrappers (gcc-ar /
+# gcc-ranlib), which CMake has already discovered, so that the archive
+# index covers the LTO symbols too.
+if(CMAKE_CXX_COMPILER_AR)
+    set(CMAKE_AR "${CMAKE_CXX_COMPILER_AR}")
+endif()
+if(CMAKE_CXX_COMPILER_RANLIB)
+    set(CMAKE_RANLIB "${CMAKE_CXX_COMPILER_RANLIB}")
+endif()
+
 # Project-wide include paths
 include_directories("${CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR}/vpu_driver/include")
 include_directories(${VPU_SOURCE_DIR})
